			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">MMC5 <em>without</em> exram is only about 300 bits. It would probably fit in an iCE40xx384, with a caveat about possibly running out of interconnect.<br /><br />Honestly, if you're using a CHR-RAM board, setting up the programmable logic to use part of the CHR-RAM for something else (say, finer attribute zones, or whatever) seems like the best choice.<br /><br />The problem with doing any sophisticated banking with a slowish microcontroller is that the microcontroller can emulate a latch very easily, but to implement, say, the 8x1KiB banking of CHR, would take an additional 74'151 for every bit of banking: up to eight, assuming 2⁸ = 256 KiB of CHR. That would also take 64 outputs from your microcontroller.<br /><br />---<br /><br />For the moment, let's calculate what it would take to do fine-grained CHR banking with a PIC18. (Only because I'm the most familiar with them).<br />The interrupt handler (and its timing) that emulates a tiny ROM is easy:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">ISR:<br />&nbsp; movff PORTB,FSR0L<br />&nbsp; movff INDF0,LATA<br />&nbsp; retfie FAST</div>It takes 1-2cy for the change on PORTB to register, it takes another 2cy to call the interrupt, and 2cy for each of the three instructions above.<br />1- This is the fastest and most unsafe version possible. We don't mask off the top bits of PORTB (containing the input banking lines), and the location of the look-up-table is fixed (and a function of what the other lines in PORTB are tied to)<br />2- We have 7-8cy from when we lines change (via the interrupt-on-change interrupt, which is acknowledged by reading from PORTB) to when we get an output, and let's assume we're working with a 70ns RAM/ROM. (Not unreasonable)<br />3- We have up to 10cy from start to finish. If we don't have more than that much time between fetches, we'll never be able to do anything but change our address lines, and we shouldn't bother using interrupts)<br />4- The PPU fetches a new byte every 2 pixels, or ¾×NTSC. This means we have 370ns. We must execute our 10 cycles in less than 37ns each in order to function as an interrupt, or we need to run the PIC at 27MIPS (a noticeable overclock from the current maximum for PIC18s at 16 MIPS)<br />5- We must get our output within 370-70=300ns, and that takes 8 cycles, or ... 37ns again. Not much to be done for it; CHR banking is just going to be a problem.<br /><br />4/5b- What if we're talking about PRG banking instead? The timing's a little kinder: 558ns/10 = 55ns or 18MIPS for interrupt-based code, and (558-70)ns/8 = 61ns or 16.4MIPS. That actually sounds like we could do it, barely.<br /><br />The Atmegas, AIUI, can be clocked faster than PICs by a little (20MIPSish rather than 16) but have noticeably longer interrupt latency (like 6-8cy instead of 3-4), so I don't know how that'll work out.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
